==Input==
{{bCommand|Input|I/O(F3):3}} is a command which will display a string and wait for the user to input a value. The value will then be stored into the specified variable once ENTER is pressed. The behavior of this command changes depending on how many parameters are passed into it, explained below.

===Syntax: Input===
{{bcode:Syntax|
:Input [''string''],[''var'']
|
* Where ''string'' is the optional string to display, and ''var'' is the optional variable to store the value to
* If ''string'' is provided, the I/O screen will display that string on a new line, then wait for user input.
* If ''string'' is not provided, the I/O screen will display a ? on a new line, then wait for user input.
* If neither ''string'' nor ''var'' is provided, it will display the graph screen and wait for the user to select a coordinate (x value of coordinate is stored into ''xc'', and the y value into ''yc'')
* Providing only ''string'' but not ''var'' results in an error ("Argument must be a variable name", ''errornum'' 140)
}}

===Ex: With String===
{{bcode:Example|
:Input "X Value",x
}}

{{bcode:Output|
X Value
5
|The value of 5 would be stored into x
}}

===Ex. Without String===
{{bcode:Example|
:Input x
}}

{{bcode:Output|
?
5
|The value of 5 would be stored into x
}}

===Ex: Without Arguments===
{{bcode:Example|
:Input
}}

[[Image:TI-89 Input Graph.jpg|320px 200px|thumb|left|Pressing ENTER here would store the coordinates into xc and yc, respectively.]]
{{-}}
==InputStr==
{{bCommand|InputStr|I/O(F3):4}} is much like input, but the values inputted into this command will always be a string (so no quotation marks are needed).

===Syntax: InputStr===
{{bcode:Syntax|
:InputStr [''string''],''var''
|
*Where ''string'' is an optional string to display instead of ?
*Where ''var'' is the variable the string inputted will be stored into
}}

===Ex: InputStr===
{{bcode:Example|
:InputStr "What is your name",name
}}

{{bcode:Output|
What is your name
George
|Pressing ENTER would store "George" into the variable ''name''.
}}

==Prompt==
{{bCommand|Prompt|I/O(F3):5}} prompts the user to input a number of variables. While this can be used to input more than one variable with one command, it does not give you the flexibility to change what is displayed on screen.

===Syntax: Prompt===
{{bcode:Syntax|
:Prompt ''var''[,''var2''][,''var3''][,…''varN'']
|
*Where ''var2'' through ''varN'' are all optional arguments. Arguments must be valid variable names.
**Amount of arguments limited only by available memory
*For each argument, Prompt will wait until a value is entered and ENTER pressed before asking for the next one.
}}

===Example: Prompt===
{{bcode:Example|
:Prompt x,y
}}

{{bcode:Output|
x?
5
y?
7
|This would store 5 into x and 7 into y
}}

==Request==
{{bCommand|Request|I/O(F3):1:2}} puts a pop-up box on the current screen and allows the user to input a string into it, and then stores that string into a variable. Request can be used as a stand-alone command or as part of a Dialog block (more on those later).

===Syntax: Request===
{{bcode:Syntax|
:Request ''string'',''var''
|
*Where ''string'' is the string to be displayed before the input box
*Where ''var'' is the variable the string gets stored into
*Request automatically turns a-lock on, so the alpha button must be pressed once before numbers and other symbols may be entered
}}

===Ex: Request===
{{bcode:Example|
:Request "name",x
}}

[[Image:TI-89 Request.jpg|thumb|left|320px 200px|The string put into the input box will be stored into the variable x.]]
{{-}}

==PopUp==
{{bCommand|PopUp|I/O(F3):1:3}} displays a pop up window with a number of choices for the user to choose between (passed in as a list). Then, the ''number'' of the choice the user selects will be stored into the variable given.

===Syntax: PopUp===
{{bcode:Syntax|
:PopUp ''itemlist'',''var''
|
*Where ''itemlist'' is a list of strings that will appear in the popup.
*Where ''var'' is the variable that the number of the choice will be stored to.
}}

===Example: Correct Equation===
{{bcode:Example|1=
:PopUp {"1+2=2","1/2=2","1-2=2","1*2=2"},x
}}

[[Image:TI-89 PopUp.jpg|thumb|left|320px 200px|When ENTER is pressed, the value 4 will be stored into x.]]
{{-}}

<noinclude></noinclude>==Passing in Arguments==
Passing in arguments is vital to functions, and can be helpful in programs as well. In order to get an argument to be passed in, it must be declared in the opening parenthesis of the program editor. Then, when calling the program (by typing <tt>prgmname()</tt> in the home screen), you put the declared arguments into the parenthesis, like so: <tt>prgmname(arg)</tt>. Note: for all of the following examples, the name of the function is "temp" (and it is a function).

===Syntax===
{{bcode:Syntax|
temp([''var1''][,''var2''][,''var3''][,…''varN''])
|
*Where ''var1'' through ''varN'' are all valid variable names
**The amount of variables passed into the function is limited only by the amount of available memory
*The variables passed in are local variables, as in they disappear the moment program execution stops (unlike from the previous ways of input, where the variables stick around until they are deleted).
}}

===Example: Temp===
{{bcode:Example|
temp(x,y,z)
:Func
:Return x^2+(y*z)/100
:EndFunc
}}

Let's say you call this program like so: <tt>temp(12,4,52)</tt>. The following will appear on your home screen:

{{bcode:Output|
▪temp(12,4,52)      146.08
}}

{{BottomNav|Output|Conditional Functions}}

