{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Snargaluff| type=Magical plant| features=very hostile| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Half-Blood Prince/Chapter 14|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'']]}}
== Overview ==
The '''''Snargaluff''''' is, in appearance, a wizened stump.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
When approached, the Snargaluff will throw out spiny branches with which it will attempt to beat those approaching it. By reaching into the opening through which these branches emerge, one can extract unpleasantly pulsating green pods, about the size of grapefruit, which in turn contain wriggling "tubers". Apart from [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Peeves|Peeves]] dropping them on people's heads in the Battle of Hogwarts in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Deathly Hallows|''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'']], no mention is made of their use.
When we first see this plant, [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]], [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Hermione Granger|Hermione]], and [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Ron Weasley|Ron]] together are caring for a Snargaluff in their Herbology class. The co-operation necessary to harvest pods from the Snargaluff is used in part as a way to smooth over difficulties between Ron and Hermione at that point, and additionally the episode is used to show that [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Neville Longbottom|Neville]], who has harvested his first pod while the Trio are still putting on their protective gear, is quite adept at Herbology in general.
It is commented in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Deathly Hallows/Chapter 20|''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'']], that along with lesser magical plants like [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Gurdyroot|Gurdyroot]]s and Dirigible Plums, [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Xenophilius Lovegood|Xenophilius Lovegood]] also has what appears to be a Snargaluff growing in his garden.
